				<div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
					<pb facs="EHRI-DC-010_01.png" n="1"/>
					<p>Statement</p>
					<p>Written with <persName ref="#ehri_dc_lewin_benjamin">Benjamin Lewin</persName>, born <date when="1926-08-17">17. 8. 1926</date>, residing in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> I., <placeName
							ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Benediktská</placeName> 4., former <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoner</term> of the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449"
							type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101076/czechowice-dziedzice.html">Čechovice</placeName>, <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-433" type="camp">Gross-Rosenu</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43" type="camp">Buchenwalde</placeName>, <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-3128" type="camp">Halberstadt</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-787" type="camp">Magdeburg</placeName>, and <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-762" type="camp">Belzig</placeName>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camps</term>. Profession electrician, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject">nationality</term> Jewish.</p>
					<p>On <date when="1944-09-28">September 28th, 1944</date>, I left on the first <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men’s</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> from <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName> to <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>. After 3 weeks in this hell, we were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transported</term> again, this time to the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor camps</term> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101076/czechowice-dziedzice.html">Čechovice</placeName> in Silesia. The <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> contained 300 people. Here, we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> 12 hours a day <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">clearing</term> away the rubble after <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombings</term>. <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">Housing</term> was slightly better than in the other places. We lived in a former <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">stable</term> that had central
						heating pipes running through it. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>, besides the long <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">working</term> hours, was very hard, and
						there was very little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. We received 1 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term>, 50 dkg of <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, and 2 dkg of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">margarine</term> a day. That was all. <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">Clothing</term> was threadbare, few people had <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shoes</term>, and we <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> outside in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject">freezing</term> cold with no <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shoes</term> on our feet. By coincidence, I managed to get myself accepted as a stubendienst because I was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-827" type="subject"
							>young</term> and I can say with certainty that this saved my life. Out of the entire <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> of 300 people, only 14 <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-561" type="subject">survived</term> and only those who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> at home. My <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> also <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101076/czechowice-dziedzice.html"
							>Čechovice</placeName> from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">pneumonia</term>, as did so many others. The front was approaching, and the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
							>Germans</placeName> wanted to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-623" type="subject">evacuate</term>. And so they did. On <date when="1945-01-15">January 15th</date>, they led us away from <placeName
							ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101076/czechowice-dziedzice.html">Čehovice</placeName> and we walked for 120 km. We made it to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3081677/wodzislaw-slaski.html">Loslau</placeName>, also in Silesia, where we were loaded onto <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train cars</term> and then we rode on. After 5 days, we arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-433" type="camp">Gross-Rosen</placeName>. The journey was
						awful. 120 of us were stuffed into 1 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">car</term>, they didn’t give us any <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, and we stayed alive only
						because we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-190" type="subject">begged</term> or <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject">stole</term> food from people at the train stations. In <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-433" type="camp">Gross-Rosen</placeName>, they brought us to a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">house</term> where we <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">slept</term> on the bare earth since there was no floor. After 4 days, they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transported</term> us to <placeName
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-43" type="camp">Buchenwalde</placeName>. Compared to the journey and the troubles we had already faced, we fared better here. After 3 weeks, they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521"
							type="subject">transported</term> us again. I found myself in the convict <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000153">Hermann</persName>-<persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000153">Göring</persName>-Werke
							<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-489" type="subject">commando</term> in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-3128" type="camp">Halberstadt</placeName>. This was a <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-503" type="subject">convict</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-503" type="subject">camp</term> for the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2950159/berlin.html">Berlin</placeName> Moabit <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject"
							>prison</term>, which was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombed</term>, and when they ran out of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">convicts</term> to add to the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term> group of former <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject">thieves</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
							type="subject">murderers</term>, who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">perished</term> in high numbers here, they simply replenished it with Jews. We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
							type="subject">worked</term> in a tunnel. We went to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> early in the morning when it was still dark, there was no <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818"
							type="subject">daylight</term> in the tunnel, and we returned from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in the evening when it was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject"
							>dark</term> once again. This was the hardest <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> ever. We were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hungry</term> and <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject">freezing</term>. We didn’t see any <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject">light</term> for 2 months. Due to my <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-827" type="subject">youth</term> I was again able to get easier <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. I tricked the Steiger by denying that I was Jewish and so
						I was given lighter <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>, during which I was able to observe the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in the tunnel. The <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> was closely monitored. If someone was too weak or tired to continue, they were thrown into a barrel of water and left there until they <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">drowned</term>. They told us that they had <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-253" type="subject">committed sabotage</term> and that <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-253" type="subject">sabotage</term> had to be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">punished</term>. After several hours, the barrel was loaded onto a cart with rocks and
						dumped together with the rocks into an embankment, which was then flattened. Hundreds of people were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-748" type="subject">buried</term> here. I was the only one from our <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-561" type="subject">survive</term>.</p>
					<p>They evacuated us further away ahead of the approaching front, and the former <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">convicts</term> and I, the only one from our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521"
							type="subject">transport</term>, made it to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-787" type="camp">Magdeburg</placeName>, where we were forced to search for unexploded <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083"
							type="subject">bombs</term> after air strikes. Thankfully, we were soon moved, and in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-762" type="camp">Belzig</placeName>, which was our next stop, we were <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term>.</p>
					<p>As a result of my troubles, I became a so-called Muselmann. After <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberation</term>, I became <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">ill</term> and
						spent several months in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>. By the time I returned to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> nobody imagined that I could have <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-561" type="subject">survived</term>.</p>
					<p><persName ref="#ehri_dc_lewin_benjamin">Lewin Benjamin</persName></p>
